# month into ordered categorical types
# Because there are only 3 types of term then this column is ordered categorical type 
#Use Function to minimize the code and reusing
def Parscat ( column , array):
    order_cat = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True,categories = array) 
    loan2[column] = loan2[column].astype(order_cat)


months = ['Jan','Feb','Mar','Apr','May','Jun','Jul','Aug','Sep','Oct','Nov','Dec']
terms = [12 ,36 ,60 ] 
Parscat('month' , months)
Parscat('Term',terms)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 99,151 loans data in the dataset with 14 features (ListingNumber, ListingCreationDate, Term, LoanStatus, BorrowerAPR, ListingCategory (numeric), BorrowerState, Occupation', 'EmploymentStatus', LoanOriginalAmount, StatedMonthlyIncome, DebtToIncomeRatio, MonthlyLoanPayment, ListingCategory).

What are the main features of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in figuring out what features are best for predicting the Loan Amount in the dataset. and Borrower APR.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your features of interest?¶

I expect that MonthlyLoanPayment and StatedMonthlyIncome will impact on the loan amount, and in Borrower APR, I expected that the Borrower APR be affected by loan amount and term.

# plot matrix of numeric features against categorical features.
# can use a larger sample since there are fewer plots and they're simpler in nature.

sample = loan2.sample(n=2000, replace = False)

def boxgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ Quick hack for creating box plots with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    default_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.boxplot(x, y, color = default_color)
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)
box_cat = ['Term','EmploymentStatus','ListingCategory']
plt.figure(figsize = [10, 20])
g = sb.PairGrid(data = sample, y_vars = ['BorrowerAPR', 'LoanOriginalAmount'], x_vars = box_cat,
                height = 3, aspect = 1.5)
g.map(boxgrid)
plt.show();

Analysis

  1. Borrowe APR

    • Term 
        Most ARP for 36 months loans
    • Employment Status 
        If we avoid other and not available classes we can say most clients are employed and retired.
    • Listing Category 
        Different borrower APR with a different category, for example, most borrower APR is for student use  and the     least is for Green loans

  2. Loan Original Amount

    • Term 
        When the amount increases, the increase is in the term
    • Employment Status 
        Employed Client is the most class are taking the loans
    • Listing Category 
       We notice here a lot of outliers, in general, the most category is Debt Consolidation and the leaves are          Household Expenses and Cosmetic Procedure.

How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

The borrower APR is negatively correlated with the loan original amount, that when an increase in loan amount the decrease in borrower annual percentage rate. It also shows that at different size of the loan amount, the APR has a large range, but the range of APR decrease with the increase of loan amount.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

A surprising interaction is that the borrower APR and loan amount is negatively correlated and I was shocked by the result of plot #2 (Loan Amount Vs Monthly loan payment and BorrowerAPR impact)because I know if you pay more per month, then you will pay off the loan more quickly so APR is less.
